			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: HP or AC?<a name="63723"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 23 04 4:14 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The answers of keiz and delanion are correct, but the key words here are in the long run. At level 52 you are still low enough that both the AC and HP routes are open to you. Being above the AC threshold here makes a big difference to your tankability and that is important.
<br />

<br />
However the point about HP is that in 3 or 4 levels you will find that even without trying you will be hitting the AC softcap and hence getting less for your AC than you may be used to at lower levels. By level 60 most bards find the value they are getting from AC to be low enough that 'pure HP' is often preached.
<br />

<br />
So my advice to you would be to either look to the long haul and not worry about AC, sacrifing some tankabilkity in the short term. Or if you already have good AC I would say keep it above 1200 but after that concentrate primarily on HP. This is probably optimal at level 52, and equates to the 'balanced' approach melodion suggests.
<br />

<br />
Just remember it isn't worth buying high AC, low HP items at the level you are now because of the short duration of usefulness they will have. So if you are currently a HP-based bard stick with that. And if you are an AC-based bard gradually phase that out over the next 8 levels with an eye on that 1200AC figure.
<br />

<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />   Zel  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />
</span></td>
